      "text": "Documents vs records ISO 14001:2015 uses the single term documented information , but in practice there are two kinds: Documents — say what you intend to do : policy, procedures, plans, registers. They are kept current and version-controlled . Records — show what actually happened : audit reports, monitoring results, training records, review minutes. They are kept as evidence and are not changed after the fact (they are retained and protected). Control of documented information (cl. 7.5) Documented information must be: Identified — title, date, author, reference/owner. Format-appropriate — language, media, review and approval. Available and suitable for use where and when needed. Protected — from loss of confidentiality, improper use or loss of integrity. Controlled — distribution, access, retrieval, retention and disposition; and version/change control for documents. What ISO 14001 explicitly expects The standard requires documented information for, among others: the EMS scope , the environmental policy , risks/aspects/obligations and their criteria, objectives , evidence of competence , communications , operational control as needed, emergency preparedness , monitoring/measurement results , evaluation of compliance , the internal audit programme and results , management review results , nonconformities and corrective actions , and improvement. See the Records & Documents Register for a ready-to-use master list modeled on typical ISO 14001 programs. In Trainovate Documents and records produced in the app (registers, findings, CAPA, conclusions, signed reports) carry author and timestamp attribution. Apply your retention schedule on top — the register lists suggested owners and retention periods.",
