      "text": "Raising a nonconformity A nonconformity is the non-fulfilment of a requirement. Record it against a specific clause with: a clear, factual statement of what was not met; the objective evidence it is based on; the clause reference (identifier and short title). Avoid speculation. If more information is needed, create a follow-up note instead of forcing a finding. Grading Grade Meaning Major NC Absence or total breakdown of a required process; significant doubt about control or conformance; legal / environmental risk; or several minors against one requirement (systemic). Blocks certification. Minor NC An isolated lapse that does not undermine the EMS overall. OFI An opportunity for improvement — not a nonconformity. Only the lead auditor sets the grade and rationale. The corrective-action loop (CAPA) Each nonconformity drives a CAPA record aligned to ISO 14001 cl. 10.2: Correction — immediate containment. Root cause — why it happened (5-whys / cause analysis). Corrective action — eliminates the cause so it cannot recur, with an owner and due date . Implementation — mark implemented once there is evidence of implementation. Verification of effectiveness — the lead auditor confirms the action worked; an effective action closes the nonconformity. Verification of effectiveness is lead-only and requires connectivity. Typical timelines: major NCs ~30 days, minor NCs ~90 days. Tracking The Findings screen highlights overdue corrective actions and open nonconformities so nothing slips before the report or the next surveillance audit.",
