      "readingMinutes": 2,
      "type": "faq",
      "html": "<h3 id=\"what-is-the-difference-between-an-aspect-and-an-impact\">What is the difference between an aspect and an impact?</h3>\n<p>An <strong>aspect</strong> is an element of your activities, products or services that can interact with the environment (e.g. discharge of wastewater). An <strong>impact</strong> is the resulting change to the environment (e.g. reduced water quality).</p>\n<h3 id=\"what-is-the-difference-between-a-major-and-a-minor-nonconformity\">What is the difference between a major and a minor nonconformity?</h3>\n<p>A <strong>major</strong> nonconformity is the absence or total breakdown of a required process, a significant doubt about control or conformance, a legal/environmental risk, or several minors against one requirement (systemic) — it blocks certification. A <strong>minor</strong> is an isolated lapse that does not undermine the EMS overall.</p>\n<h3 id=\"what-is-an-ofi\">What is an OFI?</h3>\n<p>An <strong>opportunity for improvement</strong> — a suggestion that is not a nonconformity. OFIs do not require corrective action but can inform continual improvement.</p>\n<h3 id=\"how-long-do-i-have-to-close-a-corrective-action\">How long do I have to close a corrective action?</h3>\n<p>It depends on your programme, but common defaults are about <strong>30 days</strong> for major nonconformities and <strong>90 days</strong> for minors. The lead auditor verifies effectiveness before the nonconformity is closed.</p>\n<h3 id=\"what-documents-are-mandatory-for-iso-14001\">What documents are mandatory for ISO 14001?</h3>\n<p>At minimum: the EMS scope, environmental policy, the criteria and results for aspects/obligations/risks, objectives, evidence of competence, communications, operational control as needed, emergency preparedness, monitoring and evaluation-of-compliance results, the internal audit programme and results, management review results, and nonconformity/corrective-action records. See the <strong>Records &amp; Documents Register</strong>.</p>\n<h3 id=\"how-often-are-surveillance-audits\">How often are surveillance audits?</h3>\n<p>Surveillance audits are <strong>typically annual</strong> within the three-year certification cycle, with a full recertification before the cycle ends.</p>\n<h3 id=\"what-is-evaluation-of-compliance\">What is evaluation of compliance?</h3>\n<p>A periodic check (cl. 9.1.2) that the organization is meeting its compliance obligations, supported by documented evidence of the result. It is distinct from simply listing the obligations.</p>\n<h3 id=\"who-can-perform-an-internal-audit\">Who can perform an internal audit?</h3>\n<p>A <strong>competent and impartial</strong> auditor — someone who does not audit their own work. Competence and impartiality records support this (ISO 19011 / ISO/IEC 17021-1).</p>\n<h3 id=\"does-the-policy-have-to-be-public\">Does the policy have to be public?</h3>\n<p>It must be <strong>available to interested parties</strong> and communicated within the organization. Many organizations publish it; at minimum it should be available on request.</p>",
